review.reviewBody: They need to fix the zippers on these, I own two pairs. Besides the fact that they broke on both pairs, they're great for warm-weather riding and the velcro holds up. I still wear mine and just deal with the zipper problem.
review.name: Zippers break. Won't warranty.

review.reviewBody: Im excited to try them out. I just got to get fully healed before I break out the bike
review.name: Haven’t tried them out yet.

review.reviewBody: POC's Essential Enduro shorts are extremely comfortable. Moreover, they keep me really cool during a workout. Lastly, they can handle a machine wash with ease.
review.name: Terrific shorts!

review.reviewBody:
Really let down, but at least they were cheap, they will definitely be regulated to my back up shorts. My main gripes are 
- only 2 zipper pockets and they are small, zipper is not great, still fits an i phone but that’s about it 
- adjustable Velcro straps are absolute trash, i could barely get them to stick on my first day every riding them, they often come un done, then you get the pant sag, very annoying on trails when you are in and out of the saddle 
- only 1 single button to secure the waist, would not be as big of an issue if the Velcro straps worked 
- the feel very thin, like they are going to rip with 1 snag on a tree branch or rock 

Pros
- Cost- very cheap compared to most other shorts (was trying not to spend 150$+, but will buying another pair of yetis that were bullet proof for 4 seasons 
- they look pretty cool 
- really comfortable, (when not sagging) breathe well,

I followed the recommendations to size down and that was a mistake, had to return them and order a bigger size, they fit a little narrower then what I’m used to in bike shorts but the stretch makes them not feel constrictive
review.name: Disappointed, not great design, 2.5 star

review.reviewBody:
The velcro tabs on the waist line are really flimsy, and don't stay fastened very well.  During my ride, the velcro kept coming undone, and the shorts would sag, making getting in/out of the saddle slightly annoying, as the nose of the saddle would catch the crotch of the shorts. 
Can I return them after only 1 use?
review.name: Velcro straps on waist are flimsy

review.reviewBody:
I purchased these $100 shorts knowing POC is priced higher but the quality should equal the premium? Well I was wrong . While I like the fit and function. After the first day and I didn't' even crash, I have a 3 inch tear in the middle of my left butt cheek! 
Never again. Lesson learned.
review.name: Cheap material

review.reviewBody:
Mostly commenting on size. Fabric seems light and tough and they're easy to move in but I haven't owned then long enough to comment on durability. 

I ordered a small and returned for medium. I'm usually a 32 waist, sometimes a 31 or 30, so that seemed like a good match for small. The shorts would button up but too tight and I couldn't live with the resulting muffin top.
review.name: Nice shorts, ran small for me

review.reviewBody: Shorts have a great polished slim fit with enough length to prevent any knee gap with your pads. Velcro waist band dials down the fit. The two pockets fit my iPhone Pro Max and a wallet when popping into the store. Perfect!
review.name: Perfect fit

review.reviewBody: I was hesitant to try these because earlier versions seemed to have sizing issues, but the new crop fit bang on. I typically wear a 32" or 33" waist, and the POC mediums are right on the money. Along the same lines, I usually wear 34" inseam pants, and these shorts fall just below my kneecaps. They pair really well with POC VPD Air knee pads, if you're wondering. They don't hang-up at all. The fit and feel are very similar to Pearl Izumi Summit shorts... a nice stretchy and light softshell material with a trimmer cut. Glad I bought 'em!
review.name: Love the fit and material

review.reviewBody: I bought these for reasturant dishwashing, line cooking and prep cooking. The floor at my job is ALWAYS wet. Then, after we close, we do the floors by throwing buckets of MORE water all over. So, I was looking for a comfortable boot that would somewhat keep my feet dry and enable me to move fast in my work environment. These boots did the job. They are super comfortable "right off the bat". There was no "breaking them in" time at all. Also, they kept my feet dry most of the time. As far as slip resistant, I give them 5 stars. I could and did run across the kitchen and cooler floors without slipping{and I run fast}. I am extremely active at work so the "wear and tear" on all my boots are probrably shorter than the average consumer. However, these did well considering all that I put them through.
review.name: A Perfect Transaction Satisfaction

review.reviewBody:
Pics with this review are a pair bought Jan 16 2023, a year & 5 days before this post. Used on a construction job of a pair of apartment buildings, double-digit multi-story, actually a complex complete with ground floor level retail spaces also, a large commercial project, spanning a 5-year overall schedule. 

Lots of mud, slop, gravel, concrete slurry, gooey drywall joint compound, paint, foam, fire caulking, I could go on & on. One of the pics shows a slice/cut a boot endured from a sideswipe of jagged sheetmetal. 

Amazingly, despite that, as long as not completely submerged in standing ankle-deep water that area was still 90+% water resistant/repellant. Unknown to me beforehand I discovered that the boot upper under the exterior rubber also has an inner liner that is fairly strong, and adds an extra layer that was usually just enough for most circumstances. 

Fact is.... I should have replaced these months & months ago, but they've held up so well, despite that one unfortunate incident (not the boot's fault, 100% mine).  

Know in advance these are not crosstrainers or made to simply be prepared for an occasional rain shower or shoveling snow. These are heavy, the soles are thick, and they don't bend much or break in much around ankles the way regular suede leather workboots or hiking boots do. If you are willing to accept that, and expect to be in a wet/muddy sloppy workplace or similar dirty area for an extended or prolonged amount of time then these boots are at the level of ruggedness and durability you need as opposed to local hardware store cheap rubber boots only made for light duty every once in a while, like washing your car or watering your yard with a garden hose etc. For "real work" these will handle just about anything you do (with the exception being that they are rubber can't handle abrasions or cuts from jagged edges, but then again, even leather can get cut too, but leather is not even in the same league as these for wet damp nasty sloppy other......)
review.name: For demanding tuf "real work" in wet muddy slop..

review.reviewBody: Perfect goggles for skimo. They're ridiculously lightweight, snug, and comfortable. I do have a big head (the Dynafit TLT L/XL helmet doesn't fit me even though the Radical does!) but have no size issues with these goggles, as one of the previous reviewers did.
review.name: Versatile and lightweight

review.reviewBody:
My eyes can't handle heavy wind, so I always carry a pair of goggles in my pack when I tour in case it's really gnarly out there. I'm in my sunglasses about 95% of the time for up and down, but always like to have that assurance. These goggles caught my attention due to the light weight since it's more of a pack item for me anyways. 

I was able to test them out, and they're okay. I don't have an overly giant head, but the frames are just large enough if I put them on correctly. I would not recommend them for people who are giant sized as I don't think they'll fit. Also, due to the design of the goggle strap attachment leaves giant air gaps on each side of the goggle, so it's easy for wind to sneak in. Lastly, the double frame gives me double vision if I catch the light just right. The transition feature is a nice touch and seems to work as intended.

So overall these are not good goggles, but they are better than sunglasses to keep you warmish and protect your eyes from the elements. Since they will live in my pack the majority of the time, I will keep them. I can't say I would recommend them for someone who wears goggles a ton.
review.name: Underwhelmed, but still pleased about the weight.

review.reviewBody:
There's a lot to like with these goggles as far as the light and fast concept behind it. They feel like they weigh almost nothing and they fit well with the Dynafit helmet. If you have a low nose bridge they will not work for you. I found that the lenses were not dark enough in full sun and had difficulty seeing. As far as construction, you can see the adhesive that attaches the lens to the frame and at first I thought there was a protective film on the lens but then realized it was supposed to be there. The goggle frame does not have sealing on the sides, most likely to help with air flow/fogging but did not cause any issues. As far as the product photos, the Dynafit photos show the lens a S1-S3 catergory but lists the lens as a S1-S2 (on the Dynafit website). The goggles lens came as S1-S2. The S3 rating is for bright sun so that could explain the lens not being dark enough. Look forward to the next iteration of this goggle.

Here is what I found on the lens tints: 
Category 1 / S1 – Light – Lightly tinted lenses for dull overcast and foggy days. 
Category 2 / S2 – Medium – Good all-round lens tints for the majority of weather conditions. Category 3 / S3 – Dark – Dark lenses that cut out a lot of the suns rays, ideal for sensitive eyes and bright sunny days.
review.name: Superlight, minimalist, but...

review.reviewBody: I watched these shoes for months & finally someone gifted them to me. I LOVED them & wore them frequently. I travel a lot & liked these shoes because they are lightweight, cute, & comfortable. However, about three months after receiving these shoes the sole completely separated from the shoe. I would attach photos but for some reason that's not an option. Yes, I wore the shoes frequently for walking & hiking, but they are advertised as durable & should not have broken after three months of wear. I've tried to email Teva but can't find a customer service address. I cannot attempt to exchange them because I travel full time & am currently in South Asia where I cannot mail them back. I am disappointed in the quality of these shoes, the false advertising, & Teva's customer service.
review.name: I loved these shoes until the broke after 3 months

review.reviewBody: Teva used to be high quality, but their items have become lower quality while raising the prices. I really like it the style, it's comfortable and practical. But after only having it for 3 months, it's falling apart. The sole has disconnected from the rest of the shoe. It's covered by warranty, but in order to get it replaced, you have to return it via UPS. If you're like me and live over 40 minutes from the closest UPS store, this is a huge inconvenience. They should allow USPS, or just replace the faulty item without making the customer spend more time and resources to replace a faulty product. I'm very disappointed as I have been a Teva fan for a long time.
review.name: Poorly made

review.reviewBody: I wear these sandals everywhere I can. They go well with pants, shorts, dresses and can be dressed up or down. The best part is that they are really comfortable and help alleviate my plantar fasciitis pain. I wear a 7.5 but ordered 8 and they are prefect
review.name: Super comfy and looks great!

review.reviewBody: I wore these for a full day of walking in Italy and my feet don't hurt at all! I have a very hard time finding comfortable footwear. I feel stable while walking on the cobblestone in Italy even when raining. These are the perfect sandal I can't wait to wear them again tomorrow for more walking!
review.name: Perfecto

review.reviewBody: I can't say how much I love this sandal. I was leery at first because it's not my typical sandal i would wear , however, it is a great surprise that they actually didn't feel clunky at all, which I was worried about, and they went on as smooth as a glove. I'm a size 8- 8.5, and I bought the size 8 and it was perfect for me. The adjustments you can make are so subtle but they help. The most comfortable shoe I've had in a really long time hands down. What an I gonna do once winter comes!?? I'll miss them but look forward to wearing them next season!
review.name: My new go to

review.reviewBody: Comfy shoes that you can wear all day and not have blisters or achy feet.
review.name: I love these shoes

review.reviewBody: I wear these for kicking around. They have great support.
review.name: Love fit and color

review.reviewBody: Decided to give these a try after reading reviews. I have high arches, bunions, & pain after working on concrete for almost 30 years. I have lived in these since I ordered 2 weeks ago! They are more attractive than my hokas & the adjustability of the straps is great for wide feet. Definitely ordering another color & perhaps style in the future!
review.name: Perfect sandal for troubled feet

review.reviewBody: I surfed from neuropathy and lymphadema. These shoes provide excellent support but remain 'gooshy' enough for all-day comfort. The added bonus is the limitless adjustability. Thank you Teva for a great shoe!
review.name: Awesome

review.reviewBody: I love my new sandals. They look good with many of my outfits, but most importantly, they feel so good. I can walk and dance without any ache or pain. The arch support is ideal, especially for my plantar fasciitis. Since I cannot wear my footwear inserts, I fear the non-supportive sandal - but not these!

review.name: Nice vest

review.reviewBody:
Just got the vest the other day and so far I love it. I purchased a size Large which for vests, coats and most sweaters is what I take unless it's described as a more tailored fit, then I will probably go up to XL. 

I love the vest's features, build, style and colors. It's definitely a quality vest that I really can't envision it breaking down in anyway over time.

Unfortunately it is a bit snug fitting down the chest and sides. It does fit me, but I don't think I can wear anything else but a t-shirt or a thinner long sleeve shirt. I imagine if I can lose 3-5lbs then it will fit perfect.

If I bought again, I would go up to the XL size so I could be sure to have room in case I am in a pinch and have to use a dryer rather than letting it air dry on my rack.
review.name: Very durable and quality vest

review.reviewBody: I have too many vests and really only need this one. Ideal for mild weather outer to really cold weather layering. Holding up well and provides good wind protection on the chest. Considering buying a back-up if this one is lost or damaged!
review.name: My best vest by gar

review.reviewBody: This is my go to vest for fall to early spring here in the Northeast. Windproof, soft and durable. Plus love the retro look. Much more durable than down or softshell vests. Especially great for cat lovers, as their claws won't ruin this vest when you carry them. I find them slightly under-sized.
review.name: Favorite vest

review.reviewBody:
Men's XL Natural with blue trimmings/pocket. The length goes down slightly past the waist. The vest has a meshlike barrier sewn into the vest which provides the windproof barrier and makes the vest warm.
The vest is Form Fitting (fits more closely to the body) so you can wear a shirt and lightweight fleece pullover underneath but nothing more or heavy since it'll be (too) tight! 
If you roominess, buy 1 size UP!

For whatever reason, Patagonia chose to make the vest form fitting instead of the more casual, looser fitting. Patagonia should Stop with making clothes that focus on looks over functionality!

Pockets have the barrier in front of it so your hands will be warm and small pocket holds small items like keys or money but there are no inner pockets.
It's warm while wearing in cool spring nights and should be warm for autumn/winter wear.

Hopefully, it'll wash well and won't shrink over time and the fleece stays soft.
Buy when it's on sale as Patagucci products are generally expensive!
review.name: Decent vest but form fitting!

review.reviewBody: Have had many pairs of glycerin shoes. This pair feels tight across the toe area. Otherwise they are fine
The bottoms of these have completely worn off.  So strange as I’ve never had that issue with Brooks before.  I used to love Glycerin’s, but these don’t work for me.

review.reviewBody:
Best everyday and long run trainer I've ever owned! 

I've had all sorts of foot issues and have tried at least 100 pair of shoes, different brands and models. I've owned Hokas, Altras, Saucony, Adidas, Nike.
I was desperate because after an ankle sprain, Achilles tendonitis, plantar fasciitis... Your feet become EXTREMELY picky. I mean it.

I needed to train for my first marathon this year and I was starting to lose hope. I tried the glycerin 20 and they made my feet hurt last year.

I decided to give these a shot. My feet are wider and usually have issues finding something that fits perfectly. These were like sent from heaven!!! Cushion but not too much that you feel sinking or hurting. Better than the ghost which I find too firm. No breaking in period, nothing hurts when I run with these. I feel protected, supported, my feet and joints are happy and grateful.

I got the aqua pair in 8 regular and 7.5 wide in the black. Both perfect fit!
Thanks Brooks! Nailed it!
review.name: Best shoes I've ever owned!

review.reviewBody: My favorite running shoes! Have tried soooo many other brands, I 🩵 Brooks!!!!
review.name: Best running shoes!

I’m sure they’re a wonderful shoe, although they did not work for me as I have MS and plantar fasciitis (reason for one star). I was in great hopes.

review.reviewBody:
I’m using this as flip line for my small raft. Yes it’s not its intended purpose but it fits nicely in my pocket and will work when I need it. 
I used to wrap it around my waist but the pocket is much cleaner. If it were a foot longer it would be perfect.
review.name: Great product, wish it were a little longer for my application

review.reviewBody: I'm currently busing this as a leash for my hit took by girthing it to the waist of my harness and then daisying it up to keep it out of the way. Gives me all the reach I need when I rarely need to use my tool, and could come in handy for many other uses as opposed to other leash alternatives.

I use these for extending cams on long wandering rock pitches. They lighten the load and are super easy to rack around the shoulder with one carabiner, instead of using two carbines on an alpine draw on your harness. Just open the carbine and pull it off your shoulder. Backpack straps are not an issue when you rack these over the shoulder.  If you rack each of your cams with an individual carabiner, then take two or three rabbit runners to extend placements. You can cut out a few carabiners from your rack with these. They are simple and light. They are also useful for slinging small trees.
review.name: Lighten your load

review.reviewBody: One eye is too small and long stitching on both ends limits the diameter you can use it on
review.name: One eye is too small

review.reviewBody: best runner ever, I would change all my old runners for the rabbits
review.name: best runner ever, I would

review.reviewBody: I thought this would be just what I wanted, a UHMW rabbit runner that gives in a compact package. But I really question the decision to make 1 of the loops tight, this makes it difficult to use for any function other than as a 4 foot extension. I also wish it was about 6"longer so it could be used easily for fixed and focused anchors
review.name: Needs more work

review.reviewBody: Sure to midigate rope drag. Cleaner than using a doble shoulder length easy to deploy... DMM revolver carabiner makes it even better on the really windy pitch. Off course need to place some thing much heigher safe on those big ankle buster ledge.
review.name: Great for linking pitch(s)

review.reviewBody: Living in the arctic, the problem is often wind as opposed to temperature. There's a small period of the year, when the temps start dipping in the negatives (celsius) before it gets insulated snowpants time, where it's wet, a bit chilly but still super windy. The wind is what was ripping the warmth from my legs. With merino and pants under this shell, you can comfortably go down to -25c. With these on, wind disappeared and they ensure snow stays out with the cuffs at the bottom of the legs. Go a size higher than the chart. I am 175lbs, 5"9 and a size 33 regularly. I went for Large. You can cinch the waste to fit with the integrated "belt". Fantastic pants for multiple applications and well built, but expensive.

review.reviewBody: I've had this backpack for three years now and it is holding up well. The functionality of the bag, with its three different compartments and expandability cannot be beat. I use it for commuting and occasionally as an overnight bag. However, it is slightly uncomfortable on my shoulders. The straps have little padding and are too far apart for me. (I'm a 5'4" woman). It would be nice if you offered the pack in proportions for a smaller person and in more colors.
review.name: Great backpack but not for extended carry

review.reviewBody: J'ai acheté ce sac pour mes voyage d'affaires et pour le quotidien. Il est un excellent sac intermédiaire qui peut facilement loger un gros laptop, une tablette et plusieurs documents. J'aime beaucoup les poches de rangement de toutes tailles. Pour la finition, le matériel Bluesign est très intéressant et lui donne une apparence "vintage".
review.name: Excellent sac de travail et pour le voyage

review.reviewBody: It is so comfortable on my shoulders and back - it was easy for me to carry along our recent adventures! The different pockets also made it easy to stay organized while traveling, which I love. So happy with this bag!
review.name: LOVE this versatile backpack!

review.reviewBody: After doing a ton of research and even buying another bag, I landed on this one for business travel. Along with compression cubes, you can technically use this or the 40L for one bag travel. The clamshell compartment helps to make this bag indispensable because of how you can utilize the space. The 28L Aion backpack and the matching carry-on spinner make a great pair, look phenomenal and have lots of great organizational features. I’ve never had a bad experience with a Thule product thus far. Thanks for putting your best into your products!
review.name: I returned another backpack for this one!

review.reviewBody: After returning from European travel without a decent travel pack, I immediately sought out the best pack I could find, and it turned out to be from the same company that made my wheeled luggage - Thule. My first experience with this pack was domestic business travel in the US. Three days of clothing and computer fit easily in the Aion, and there was room to spare. The rugged ballistic cloth held up to all the rigors of plane travel, and access to necessities was easy to reach when needed. I definitely recommend the Aion travel pack.
review.name: A travel pack like no other!

review.reviewBody: I did a lot of research before choosing the Thule Aion backpack for internacional travel.  I was not disappointed, the pack is well make from tough materials.  Large enough to hold about half my stuff for a 10 day trip.  Looking forward to putting it through its paces here in about two weeks.
review.name: THULE aion.  Exactly what I was looking for.

review.reviewBody: Love my Thule Aion 28L! Holds as much as my spinner did, but now my hands are free when traveling!

This is the best backpack for lugging around a computer everywhere you go. Very comfortable, the zippers feel awesome to use, the pockets are well placed. Space is great, I use it for a daily, I carry a few ergonomic items like a laptop stand, small bluetooth keyboard, mousepad and wrist rest and it all fits in nicely, and it has tons of space while not feeling too bulky or baggy. I will also use it when I travel, and it likely has enough space where I can bring this as an only bag on a high percentage of trips. Highly Reccomend
review.name: Great Quality, Awesome Flexibility

review.reviewBody: I travel for work often and was excited to come across this bag. The bag is okay, the straps are disappointing. Narrow enough to cut into my chest and shoulders when I have the bag filled (which is always because I only pack carry-on). The material inside the straps seems cheap and I can’t imagine it will hold up very long. The straps also attach to the bag about 2 inches below the top of the bag, and offer no way to snug the top of the bag closer to your shoulders. It ends up hanging low and leans out from the shoulder making the weight feel more awkward and not totally secure. There’s a cross-chest strap that helps, but doesn’t fix the issue.
review.name: Decent bag, not thrilled with the straps

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is the most attractive cooler that I have ever seen! We LOVE it! It's size is perfect for taking the kids to sports practice, a picnic for two, just spending a few hours or afternoon at the park, taking some drinks to a friend's dinner, or something like that, without having to haul your big cooler around. The straps are soft and feel great to hold. The entire cooler feels durable and heavy-duty while looking like a luxury cooler. The cooler keeps ice cold longer than it says it does so far. Even when it's full, it's not too heavy or uncomfortable to carry on your shoulder. Now I need this in a huge size for full days or weekends!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This cooler is awesome! The style is expensive looking and sheek all while having a purpose. The leather strap is beautiful and the shape of the color makes it modern. Perfect of bribing drinks to music in the park or things like that. It’s sturdy and easy to wipe clean too!

I enjoy using it and I’ve considered getting my kids one in the future. I would like to get more in different sizes and colors.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is flat out the most classy looking cooler I have ever owned!  Not only does it look fantastic, it is built rock solid.  The latch is heavy duty and won't accidentally pop open like some other coolers I have owned in the past.  It holds ice for a looong period of time as well.  This is the cooler you want to take to your neighbors holiday party and show up in style. I have used it for Thursday night football games with my buddies. It easily holds a 6 pack and enough ice to last you all evening. My wife however is hogging it for gatherings with her girlfriends! It easily holds 3 bottles of wine as well and she has tested that on numerous occasions!  It appears I'm going to have to purchase a second unit if I want to use it on a regular basis but that's just fine with me!
review.name: Durable and extremely classy cooler!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This Coleman Cooler is now my go to cooler for all backyard parties and cookouts its stylish design always catches people's eyes and we get questions and compliments galore. This cooler has a sturdy design its fully insulated and  has a sturdy latch and does not leak. It easily fits three wine bottles or about 7 cans with a small bag of ice and it keeps them cold for an uber amount of hours. It has a sturdy comfortable strap. I love the height of the cooler it's not like traditional coolers it save's  space when packing a vehicle it does not take  up allot of room. Coleman gets a thumbs up on this product!!.
review.name: 1900 11 QT Cooler

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This has got to be the coolest cooler that I've ever had!  Love the way it looks. The heavy-duty hinges and latch, coupled with the shiny surface is really great.  It is very well constructed, with a tight seal when closed.  It feels almost like if the military made a cooler- this would be it. My only slight complaint is that the thick leather strap isn't adjustable.  But really, I am very happy with it.  Seems like it will last forever.
review.name: Love This Cooler!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This Coleman Cooler is beautiful.  With the tall sleek design, the soft leather handles, and the beautiful color this cooler is a great statement piece. The tall and slender design makes this cooler easy to slide behind your backseat. The adjustable leather strap makes it easy to carry over your shoulder, or you can use the soft leather handle on top to carry it. The latch is very easy to open and close. This cooler is very well made and should last a very long time.
review.name: Beautiful Cooler

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] We have been meaning to buy a cooler that we can easily drag everywhere.. We want something that is sturdy enough to hold a bunch of food and beverages inside yet smaller than the one that we have. This Coleman - 1900 SB COOLER 11QT 6156  is perfect for our need. You can easily carry it with its shoulder strap plus the body is made of steel which can last for years. This is perfect for picnic or porch party at home.
review.name: Perfect for picnic!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Wow!  I love this cooler.  It was certainly built more durable than any cooler I have ever owned.  It has leather straps...a touch metal exterior, and just looks rugged.  It fits perfectly in my truck and is good for game day, road trips and overnights. I can tell this thing is going to last forever...even if I am really hard on it.  Awesome value.
review.name: SOLID!

It?s small enough to not feel bulky and big enough to carry my phone, wallet, keys, tools and sunglasses when I?m not using them.

review.reviewBody: This is a nicely made jacket, and the orange color is exactly what I was looking for, but it just didn't work out. I'm usually wear a medium jacket. review.name: Pop of Color!

review.name: Just right

hasVariant.description: Buy the Goal Zero Ranger 300 Briefcase Solar Panel online or shop all Hike & Camp from Backcountry.com.

review.reviewBody: Update.. for those of you who cannot use Goal Zero panels for some reason, maybe you should look into a electric start generator. Just sayin.
review.name: Goal Zero solar panels

review.reviewBody:
Pros:
-- It is lighter
-- It has more power
-- Less concern of cracking the panels
-- Better bag design makes it easier to remove and replace

Cons:
-- Awkward, harder for a single person to set up by themselves
-- No way to secure it in briefcase mode other than holding the handles together or stuffing it into the bag, no clips like on the Boulder 200
-- Cheap construction means the edges are wearing down quickly.  The corners are not reinforced metal like on the Boulder 200; they have thin plastic protectors that are grinding away.  Paint along the bottom is quickly scraping off due to being so close to the ground.  See photos for examples after a single day of use.

Final thoughts:
I now own both this and a Boulder 200 and while the 300 has some advantages if I bought again I would go with another Boulder.  It is designed to last and this 300 just feels like they cut too many corners.
review.name: Decent But Not Durable

review.reviewBody: I have the Ranger 300, Nomad 200, two Nomad 100, and a Nomad 50. On a sunny day with all the panels chained I can get @ 485 watts draining into my yeti 1500.. I can charge my mower batteries, my power tool batteries, and run a small fridge no problem. if you can imagine a bee hive (YETI) and worker bees, (smaller batteries) then you can really power pretty much anything with the Goal Zero setup. Oh, and I have experimented let me tell you. Thanks Goal Zero, very impressed.
review.name: Goal Zero solar panels

review.reviewBody:
Performance is good, can hit nearly 300w in ideal conditions. The wiring quality is good, serviceability of wiring is standard solar panel stuff. 

The legs are far from desirable. While the intent was to simplify the deployment and put-away, they do not perform well to hold the panels, the panel tilt cannot be adjusted, the side panels are just hanging and begging for a small gust of wind to topple the whole kit over. I find myself having to get a bit creative with ground stakes and bungee cables to hold things in place and this seems to do the job. 

The panel is big and heavy enough while folded up that the cheap fabric case is quite cumbersome to manage by yourself. Mine had endured about 20 deployments now and the zipper teeth of the case are already looking pretty ugly, the case is absolutely not going to last. Other brands semi-hard cases that hold shape are a far superior design. 

The plastic corners on the panel frames are useless, they are brittle and crack when barely bumped. I tore all of them off to avoid unknowingly leaving them behind at campsites. The other brand that rhymes with "energy" executes a perfect weather and foolproof design throughout although their panels do not meet this Goal Zero 300w ouput.
review.name: Panels are great, design is not.

review.reviewBody:
This is my second review of the same product but I couldn't see a way to edit the original review.
My weather ap says winds of 16 MPH max and my handheld wind meter measured 10.7 MPH and my panel is on its face.  Gusts over 16 MPH were certainly possible, but be advised.   GZ has no rating for wind speeds in the user guide.  The Boulder panels, due to the higher weight ratio are still standing.  The panel should be pretty easy to stake down, but you'll be supplying your own stakes.  

Looks like it has been about 3 months since my original review and the power keeps flowing from the panel, so thumbs up for that (I did have a competitor's panel fail after a few weeks once). 

Also, I did try to click on the terms & conditions link to see if I am violating them by posting a second review, but the link takes me to the product page.  So, GZ if you have any issues with this, I'd be glad to consolidate my reviews or work with you in good faith.
review.name: Wind effects

review.reviewBody:
Good things first:
The company ships fast and the packaging is good.
It works.  I get about 70% of the 300W generation at peak time/conditions at 37° 20' N.
It is light and compacts nicely.
They provide a nice velcro strap for the cord. 

Bad things:
The plastic corners keep popping off and two have broken. 
It is big and is trick to deploy without a second person.
The bag came with a tear in it. Not a big deal, but disappointing.  

Other things:
It is shorter than the Boulder 200 and taller than the Boulder 100.
It is quite wide, which could be an issue with shadows.
Goal Zero doesn't provide a way to penetrate a wall with their Anderson Powerpole cables/connectors.  I worked something up with some stuff I bought online that works well, but GZ should make something.  Also, I ended up having to slice a bit of the fingerproof guard off to make them mate up with the third party stuff but that wasn't too hard.  But don't get me wrong, I actually really like the fingerproof design and would have loved to find a solution that didn't involve a saw.
The frame is intact so far, but due to the lightness, I feel the need to be gentle with it.  The legs basically unfold themselves, which is different from the other panels in the Boulder series.  I hope they last.

I've had really good luck with the other boulder panels, the two Yeti powerstations, the home integration kit, the expansion tanks, the external charger, and every cable, combiner, and case.
review.name: Shoddy work from an otherwise good company

review.reviewBody: We began using this Ranger 300 solar array three weeks ago, and it has produced 245 watts in slightly hazy sunshine. Its solar efficiency (actual output / rated output) has exceeded that of our Nomad 200 and Nomad 100 solar arrays, and has been roughly comparable to our Boulder 200 array. Compared to the Boulder 200, the Ranger 300 provides 50% more power while weighing 3 pounds less and folding more compactly for storage. Haven't had to clear bird droppings from this non-glass cover, yet, so we can't comment about ease of cleaning. We chose to reinforce the carrying case with corrugated panels to protect the Ranger 300 solar panels when stored. The Ranger 300 has excellent power/weight ratio, and storage size.
review.name: Excellent power/weight ratio, and storage size

review.reviewBody: Incredibly easy to understand and use. Best solar panel on the market, easily.
review.name: Best Solar Panel on the market!

review.reviewBody: If your looking to buy a portable solar panel this is the one and only!! It’s has a little weight on it. Other than that it’s awesome!!
review.name: Ranger 300 is a Powerful Solar Panel!!

review.reviewBody: Love this solar panel so much - it is huge, but easy to move around. I love that it is lighter than the Boulder 200 - but more powerful! I wish they would make the Ranger in 100 & 200 versions - talk about a true lightweight solar panel.
review.name: Love it - powerful & lightweight

review.reviewBody: So pumped about these skis, can't wait to backcountry with them. So light weight
review.name: Love these

review.reviewBody: I've been on these for 4 days this season, and they are phenomenal under a variety of conditions. Light and lively on variable conditions and sublime in fresh powder. The biggest surprise was the lack of chatter and confident stability on frozen chunky crud. I am absolutely loving these skis. I am coming off of an older set of Elan Himalayas, and the feel and ease of the Helios are almost effortless. I downsized from a 102 to a 95 width, but almost no difference in the float factor. The skis are very light, and remarkably stable at speeds on hard pack and icy, windblown hellscapes. I paired these up with some Dynafit Radical bindings that I received for Christmas. I'm 6'1", 165 pounds and mid 50's in age and went with the 176s, so this set up and size specs were perfect for me. I have half a bad ACL on the left side, so I have to be weary and be slightly cautious at times. Light and strong gear is the way to go.
review.name: Backcountry Bliss

review.reviewBody:
I work in the Snowsports industry but I am also a minimalist, and I wanted a pair of skis that I could use for both touring and the resort. 

I tested out a demo pair of these at a backcountry ski area in Colorado and really liked how they performed in variable terrain, how light they felt, and how comfortable they felt (I had tried out some other skis that were marketed as touring skis and were a little wider but they felt too heavy and were harder for me to control in the trees). 

I purchased a pair of these and put a pair of shift bindings on them and oh boy howdy am I pleased with my decision. I took them on groomers, powder runs, tree trails, off-piste, and in a super pipe just for fun and they were pretty versatile and felt pretty good in most situations. I have other skis that are slightly more narrow and are my daily drivers while I’m working at the resort, but I’m chuffed I found these for touring and free-ski days at the mountain. 

For reference- I’m 5’9” and 125 lbs and I got the 169 length
review.name: Quite Delighted

review.name: Super comfy

review.reviewBody:
I’ve only run 34K in the WINTER CROSS SPIKE across four runs, but these have already been a game changer for me. Living in a place with heavy snow, rain, and ice, my winter running routine has typically involved the treadmill, only running on streets when conditions were clear. The risk of slipping on ice kept me off the roads—until now.

I’ve been eyeing these spikes for years, but every time I almost bought them, they’d sell out. This year, I finally pulled the trigger when the 2024 version came out, and I'm so glad I did. The grip is incredible, even on slush and random ice. Today, after a heavy snowfall that covered the slush and ice, the traction was amazing.

That said, there’s still a small chance of slipping—just like with studded tires, they do have limits. But for the most part, I feel safe and confident running on winter trails. They're comfortable, true to size, and keep my feet warm and dry. My only challenge now is getting in and out of my house without damaging my wooden deck and steps!
review.name: Winter Cross Spike: Game Changer for Winter Run

review.reviewBody: Very comfortable as soon as you slip your feet in. The gaiter is high enough and it's soft and moves with you. The carbide spikes provide increased grip and it gives me confidence. The lugs are also pretty good on snowy surfaces.
review.name: Very comfortable winter shoe

review.reviewBody: This is my fourth pair of spike cross shoes. I live in Canmore Alberta. Our trails get extremely icy. No other winter shoes work as well.
review.name: Winter cross spike

review.reviewBody: These shoes are a must in the winter if you are an outdoor, all year runner.  In the winter where snow and freezing and thawing makes the trail uneven, icy and slippery one feels as surefooted as can be in these shoes.  They are water and windproof and keep your feet warm and dry.  On tops of that they are great running shoes.  I could not be happier with them.
review.name: Great in winter

review.reviewBody: These are everything I expected from Salomon!  They fit great, and are really comfortable.  The spikes are excellent on this leftover snow that’s been topped with freezing rains and a slow thaw.  Our trails are sheets of chunky ice right now and, with the Cross Spike shoe, I was able to get out and run without issue.  I love the high ankle collar to keep ice and debris out. Great touch!  I recommend these shoes wholeheartedly.  I feel the fit is true to size.
review.name: Great traction and fit

review.reviewBody: I live in Utah and trail run in the winter. I run up the side of a mountain in snow and ice. The grip on these shoes enables me to run on ice without slipping - it has metal spikes protruding from the bottom. Also, the outer covering prevents snow from coming into my shoes. These are a must if you want to run in snow or icy weather.
review.name: These shoes are INCREDIBLE

review.reviewBody: Very comfy, but my usual size fits too big. Should have order 1/2 size smaller...
review.name: Confortable but fits large

review.reviewBody: Great runner with awesome grip. These made me forget that ice is slippery.
review.name: Great runner with awesome grip

review.reviewBody: This shoe fills the gap for winter training. With so much ice in this area, this shoe allows us to be out and off the treadmill. All the right features, cushion, grip, and element protection.
review.name: All the right features

review.name: Use this for literally everything

review.reviewBody: Lightweight, strong, easy to use. This is the one to add to your set.
review.name: Perfection.

review.reviewBody: she does everything she needs too! I like to clip my extra slings & what not into this. originally got this for my belay device before i learned that it’s not a super solid biner to run rope through, but at the end of the day it does everything it needs too :).
review.name: she does everything she needs too

review.reviewBody:
If you’re looking for a manual screw gate, this carabiner has you covered. The marking for “closed” versus “open” is clear & visible. I don’t have any issues with getting the screw gate to begin rotating.

I typically use these carabiners as part of my quad anchor. If you’re looking for something that’ll do the job & be budget-friendly, the hot forge is a good item to add to your gear.

I’ve owned several Positron Carabiners and figured I should update and grabbed a few Hot Forge to replace them. The hot forges are significantly smaller which has its pros and cons. It’s very compact on my harness and is great to rack gear with. On the flip side it’s a pain to use for a double rope rappel, it’s tough to get the locker open with two strands of rope running through it.

Additionally, I’ve only owned the hot forge for a few months and have maybe rappelled 10 pitches and I already have a noticeable groove. I have positrons I’ve rappelled over 50 pitches with that still don’t have grooves so not too thrilled with that
review.name: It’s okay

review.reviewBody: Super light and strong, easy to use without looking at it. Great price.
review.name: Great locking biner

review.reviewBody: Great quality for a locker on the lower end of the price range. Never had a problem with these and I trust them on every climb.
review.name: Great carabiner

review.reviewBody: I used this carabiner for the first time last night with my ATC-XP for belaying at the local gym. It was really nice having a really lightweight carabiner with an already light belay system. Overall, it was a little odd at first to have something so light, but I got used to it fast and found it really comfortable.
review.name: Comfortable Light Biner for Belaying
